---
// Privacy policy for the Silo client apps. Linked from the Play Store /
// App Store listings, so this URL (/privacy) must stay stable and public.
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import Bottombar from "../components/Bottombar.astro";
import SiloBars from "../components/SiloBars.astro";
import { SITE } from "../data/siteConfig";

const EFFECTIVE = "July 1, 2026";
const CONTACT_EMAIL = "feedback@siloserver.org";
---

<Base
  title="privacy policy"
  description="Privacy policy for the Silo client apps. Silo apps collect no analytics and send your data only to the server you point them at."
>
  <header class="policy-bar">
    <a class="policy-bar__brand" href="/">
      <SiloBars size="sm" />
      <span>{SITE.name}</span>
    </a>
    <nav class="policy-bar__nav" aria-label="Primary">
      <a href="/">home</a>
      <a href="/docs">docs</a>
      <a href={SITE.github.orgUrl}>github ↗</a>
    </nav>
  </header>

  <main id="main" class="policy">
    <article class="policy__body">
      <p class="policy__eyebrow">legal / 01</p>
      <h1>Privacy Policy — Silo Apps</h1>
      <p class="policy__meta">Effective {EFFECTIVE}</p>

      <p class="policy__lede">
        Silo is self-hosted software. The Silo apps exist to connect to a
        server that <em>you</em> (or someone you know) run. We do not operate
        accounts, we do not run analytics, and we do not receive your media
        library, watch history, or personal information. The short version:
        <strong>your data goes to your server, not to us.</strong>
      </p>

      <h2>1. Scope</h2>
      <p>
        This policy covers the first-party Silo client applications: Silo for
        Android, Silo for Android TV, Silo for iOS, Silo for tvOS, and Silo
        for macOS (together, "the apps"), published by the Silo project. A
        short note on this website is included at the end. It does not cover
        the Silo server software you install yourself, or third-party apps
        that can connect to a Silo server.
      </p>

      <h2>2. Data we collect</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>None.</strong> The apps contain no analytics, no advertising,
        no crash-reporting service, and no tracking SDKs. They do not create
        an account with us and do not transmit usage data, identifiers, or
        telemetry to the Silo project.
      </p>

      <h2>3. Data the apps store on your device</h2>
      <p>To function, the apps keep some data locally on your device:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>the address of the Silo server you enter;</li>
        <li>
          the sign-in token issued by your server after you log in, so you
          stay signed in;
        </li>
        <li>
          cached metadata and artwork for your library, and playback
          positions, so browsing and resume are fast;
        </li>
        <li>media you explicitly download for offline playback;</li>
        <li>app settings and preferences.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        This data stays on the device. Uninstalling the app (or clearing its
        data in system settings) removes all of it.
      </p>

      <h2>4. Where your data goes</h2>
      <p>
        The apps communicate with exactly one place: the Silo server whose
        address you configure. Sign-in credentials, playback progress, search
        queries, and streaming requests all go to that server and nowhere
        else. Who can see that data is governed by whoever operates the
        server — for most people, that's themselves. We recommend serving
        Silo over HTTPS; whether the connection is encrypted depends on how
        the server is set up.
      </p>

      <h2>5. Accounts and deletion</h2>
      <p>
        User accounts live on your Silo server, not with us. They are created
        and deleted by the server's administrator using the server's admin
        tools. If you use someone else's Silo server and want your account or
        history deleted, contact the person who runs it. We have no access to
        any server's accounts and cannot delete data we never receive.
      </p>

      <h2>6. Push notifications</h2>
      <p>
        Notifications the apps show for playback controls and download
        progress are generated locally on the device and involve no external
        service.
      </p>
      <p>
        Remote push notifications are optional and off unless you and your
        server administrator enable them (currently available on Apple
        platforms; Android support is planned). If you enable them, your Silo
        server sends a content-free request to Silo's push relay so the
        notification can be delivered through the platform push service
        (Apple Push Notification service, or Google's Firebase Cloud
        Messaging when Android support ships). The relay does not receive
        notification titles, message bodies, media names, user names, profile
        names, or your server URL. It does process technical metadata needed
        to deliver and operate the service: an opaque deployment identifier,
        push delivery timing and request status, the app topic, the IP
        address your server uses to contact the relay, and a hashed device
        push token. Apple or Google may also process standard delivery
        metadata under their own policies. Pushes are generic; the app
        fetches the actual content directly from your server after being
        woken up.
      </p>

      <h2>7. App permissions</h2>
      <p>The Android apps request only what playback needs:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Internet / network state</strong> — to reach your server
          and adapt streaming quality;
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Foreground services and wake lock</strong> — to keep audio
          playing and downloads running with the screen off;
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Notifications</strong> — to show local playback controls
          and download progress;
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>TV channel/EPG access (Android TV only)</strong> — to
          publish your library's rows and channels into the Android TV home
          screen.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        No permission is used to collect data for us. The apps do not request
        location, contacts, camera, or microphone access.
      </p>

      <h2>8. Third parties</h2>
      <p>
        The apps are distributed through Google Play and the Apple App Store.
        Those platforms may collect install, crash, and diagnostics data
        under their own privacy policies, independently of us. Beyond the
        optional push relay described above and the platform stores, the apps
        integrate no third-party services.
      </p>

      <h2>9. Children</h2>
      <p>
        The apps are general-audience tools for accessing a media server and
        are not directed at children. We collect no data from anyone,
        children included.
      </p>

      <h2>10. This website</h2>
      <p>
        siloserver.org is a static site hosted on GitHub Pages and runs no
        analytics of ours. GitHub may log standard access data (such as IP
        addresses) as the host, per GitHub's privacy statement, and the site
        loads web fonts from Google Fonts, which involves a request to
        Google's servers.
      </p>

      <h2>11. Changes to this policy</h2>
      <p>
        If the apps' data practices change — for example, when Android push
        support ships — we will update this page and its effective date.
        Because we collect nothing, changes will almost always be additions
        of detail, not new collection.
      </p>

      <h2>12. Contact</h2>
      <p>
        Questions about privacy? Open an issue on
        <a href={SITE.github.orgUrl}>GitHub</a> or email
        <a href={`mailto:${CONTACT_EMAIL}`}>{CONTACT_EMAIL}</a>.
      </p>
    </article>
  </main>
  <Bottombar />
</Base>

<style>
  .policy-bar {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: space-between;
    gap: 1rem;
    max-width: var(--container);
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 1.1rem 1.5rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);
  }
  .policy-bar__brand {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.55rem;
    font-family: var(--ff-display);
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.02em;
    color: var(--ink);
    text-decoration: none;
  }
  .policy-bar__nav {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1.25rem;
    font-family: var(--ff-mono);
    font-size: 0.8rem;
  }
  .policy-bar__nav a {
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    text-decoration: none;
  }
  .policy-bar__nav a:hover {
    color: var(--blue);
  }

  .policy {
    max-width: var(--container-narrow);
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 3rem 1.5rem 4.5rem;
  }
  .policy__eyebrow {
    font-family: var(--ff-mono);
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--ink-mute);
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
  }
  .policy h1 {
    font-family: var(--ff-display);
    font-size: clamp(2.1rem, 5vw, 3.2rem);
    font-weight: 800;
    line-height: 1.05;
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .policy__meta {
    font-family: var(--ff-mono);
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: var(--ink-mute);
    margin: 0 0 2rem;
  }
  .policy__lede {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--ink-soft);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--blue);
    padding-left: 1rem;
    margin: 0 0 2.5rem;
  }
  .policy h2 {
    font-family: var(--ff-display);
    font-size: 1.35rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    margin: 2.2rem 0 0.6rem;
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .policy p,
  .policy li {
    font-family: var(--ff-body);
    font-size: 0.98rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--ink-soft);
  }
  .policy p {
    margin: 0 0 0.9rem;
  }
  .policy ul {
    margin: 0 0 0.9rem;
    padding-left: 1.4rem;
  }
  .policy li {
    margin-bottom: 0.35rem;
  }
  .policy a {
    color: var(--blue);
  }
  .policy strong {
    color: var(--ink);
  }
</style>
